This paper deals with the spread of infections in social networks, which is a topic that falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also uses a spatial preferential attachment (SPA) network to model the network structure, which falls under the category of social dynamics (cs.SD). Additionally, the paper uses stochastic susceptible-infected-recovered (SIR) processes to model the spread of infections, which falls under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also discusses the behaviour of high degree vertices in the network, which falls under the category of social network analysis (cs.SN). Finally, the paper uses simulations to support its theoretical results, which falls under the category of computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.CE).
